<section class="hero">
    <h2>Remembering Albert W. Adams</h2>

    <p>
        Albert W. Adams was the son of Earl R. Adams and Kathleen Healy Adams
        of 132 Bay Spring Avenue in Barrington, Rhode Island. He attended
        Peck High School before entering the United States Navy in January 1942.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="mission">

    <h2>Barrington Connection</h2>

    <p>
        The Adams family were congregants of St. Luke's Church. Albert's family
        endured the loss of two sons during World War II. His younger brother,
        Earl R. Adams Jr., served in the Merchant Marine and was also killed
        during the war.
    </p>

    <h2>Military Service</h2>

    <p>
        Albert W. Adams served in the United States Navy as a Baker 3rd Class
        aboard the submarine USS <em>Trout</em> (SS-202).
    </p>

    <h2>Circumstances of Death</h2>

    <p>
        On April 8, 1945, USS <em>Trout</em> was lost while on patrol after
        being sunk by Japanese depth charges. All 81 men aboard were lost at sea.
    </p>

    <p>
        Albert W. Adams was 24 years old.
    </p>

    <h2>Burial and Memorial</h2>

    <p>
        Because he was lost at sea with USS <em>Trout</em>, Albert W. Adams is
        remembered among the United States Navy personnel who gave their lives
        in the Pacific during World War II.
    </p>

    <h2>Archival Materials</h2>

    <p>
        Memorial banners, photographs, military records, newspaper articles,
        submarine records, and additional historical materials may be added
        to this archive as they become available.
    </p>

</section>

